EFFECTIVENESS OF NICOTINE GUMS

Mohamed Amine Krichene

October 12, 2018

Introduction

Nicotine chewing gum has been tested several times , often inconclusive. We will analyze 26 of them, the criterion of judgment being the cessation of smoking during at least 6 months. We want to estimate the log-OR of stopping treatment of patients from treated group versus a control group by comparing twho bayesian models.

Data Presentation

The dataset is loaded from “HSAUR” library in R. qt represents the number of stops in the group treated,tt the total number of subjects in the group, qc and tc their equivalents in the control group.

library(HSAUR)
## Loading required package: tools
data("smoking",package="HSAUR")
head(smoking)

Fixed effect model

Frequentist Approach

We will use the R functions contained in rmeta.

The pooled OR is estimated at 1.67, its 95% confidence interval is of [1.47; 1.90].

library(rmeta)
meta.MH(smoking$tt,smoking$tc,smoking$qt,smoking$qc,names=rownames(smoking))
## Fixed effects ( Mantel-Haenszel ) Meta-Analysis
## Call: meta.MH(ntrt = smoking$tt, nctrl = smoking$tc, ptrt = smoking$qt, 
##     pctrl = smoking$qc, names = rownames(smoking))
## Mantel-Haenszel OR =1.67    95% CI ( 1.47, 1.9 )
## Test for heterogeneity: X^2( 25 ) = 34.9 ( p-value 0.09 )

Bayesian Approach

Statistic model

We will consider the following model: \[q_i^T\sim\mathcal{B}(p_i^T,t_i^T)\] \[q_i^C\sim\mathcal{B}(p_i^C,t_i^C)\] \[logit(p_i^T)\sim\alpha_i+\beta\] \[logit(p_i^C)\sim\alpha_i\]

R implementation

library(R2OpenBUGS)
sink("modele_fixe.txt")
cat(" model{
  for (i in 1:N) {
qc[i] ~ dbin(pc[i], tc[i])
  qt[i] ~ dbin(pt[i], tt[i])
  logit(pc[i]) <- alpha[i]
  logit(pt[i]) <- alpha[i] + beta
  alpha[i]~ dnorm(0.0,1.0E-6)
}
beta~dnorm(0.0,1.0E-6)
or<-exp(beta)}",fill=T)
sink()
N=26
dt=list(N=26,qc=smoking$qc,tc=smoking$tc,qt=smoking$qt,tt=smoking$tt)
dt
inits<-function(){
  inits=list(beta=rnorm(1),alpha=rnorm(N))
}
params <- c("beta","alpha","or")
filename<-"modele_fixe.txt"

Convergence analysis

In Bayesian analysis, OR is estimated at 1.7, its range of credibility at [1.5; 1.9]. The Geweke diagnostics shows the stationary of the generated sample.
